    </script><meta content="LearningHindi" property="fb:admins" /><meta content="Learning Hindi!" property="og:site_name" /><meta content="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/1021543673/intro-3-devanagari-the-hindi-alphabet" property="og:url" /><meta content="article" property="og:type" /><meta content="So in&nbsp;Intro #1: About Hindi&nbsp;you may remember that it was briefly mentioned that Hindi is written in what&rsquo;s called the Devanagari script. Here&rsquo;s I&rsquo;m going to introduce you to some of the main concepts of this. Unfortunately we&rsquo;re not going to be able to learn to read and write overnight, but slowly, step by step we&rsquo;ll get there!


 Devanagari, or&nbsp;&#2342;&#2375;&#2357;&#2344;&#2366;&#2327;&#2352;&#2368;, is the name of the alphabet that Hindi is written in. Devanagari is also used to write other languages, like Sanskrit, Nepali, Marathi and so on. Each language has it&rsquo;s own slight modification to the alphabet - this is just like how the Latin alphabet (the one we&rsquo;re using here!) is used for other languages like Spanish and French, which have their own modifications - like the letter &eacute; in French and &ntilde; in Spanish.





These are the Hindi vowels - do you recon they look a little scary? Well don&rsquo;t be put off, we&rsquo;re here to teach you it all!


 Now I&rsquo;m going to tell you a fact you might not believe, ready? Compared to English, Hindi is much much easier to read! See I told you you wouldn&rsquo;t believe me. So let me tell you why. This about the words &lsquo;cat&rsquo; and 'city&rsquo;, these both start with the letter 'c&rsquo;, but they start with different sounds! Cat starts with a 'k&rsquo; sound and city and &rsquo;s&rsquo; sound. Confusing hey! In Hindi every letters always has the same pronunciation*.


 So let&rsquo;s learn a few things about Devanagari. Firstly the most distinctive look about it is the horizontal line that&rsquo;s above almost all the letters, it looks like a washing line with the letters hanging from it!





namaste aap kaise hain? - Hello, how are you? Notice how the letters hang from the red 'washing line&rsquo;


 There are no capital letters in Devanagari - which makes our life a lot easier! We use something called a transliteration to help us read the Hindi words, what does this mean? Well for example here&rsquo;s a Hindi word: &#2346;&#2381;&#2351;&#2366;&#2352; it means 'love&rsquo; in Hindi. A transliteration tells us how to pronounce this word by writing it in English letters, so for this word we&rsquo;d write pyaar - that&rsquo;s approximately how the word is pronounced! The transliteration will always be in italics - but you should not learn to rely on it!





Everyone gets confused learning new things  - but stick with it and you&rsquo;ll get there!


 Punctuation marks are exactly the same as English ones but sometimes you&rsquo;ll see a&nbsp;&#2404; which means exactly the same as a full stop (/period).


 Hopefully this has given you enough background information for you to progress on to the&nbsp;Hindi Vowels&nbsp;and&nbsp;Hindi Consonants&nbsp;sections&nbsp;where you start to learn the letters of Devanagari in detail:


 Hindi Vowels


 Hindi Consonants


 Are you having problems displaying Devanagari correctly on your computer? Have a look here to hopefully solve your issues.&nbsp;


 *Ok I lied slightly, not 100% always. But the number of exceptions to the rules are microscopic especially when compared to English!" property="og:description" /><meta content="Intro #3: Devanagari - The Hindi Alphabet!" property="og:title" /><style type="text/css">p.center { text-align: center; }

