    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="intro-3-devanagari-the-hindi-alphabet">Intro #3: Devanagari - The Hindi Alphabet!</a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>So in&nbsp;<a href="../706242869/into-1-about-hindi">Intro #1: About Hindi</a>&nbsp;you may remember that it was briefly mentioned that Hindi is written in what&rsquo;s called the Devanagari script. Here&rsquo;s I&rsquo;m going to introduce you to some of the main concepts of this. Unfortunately we&rsquo;re not going to be able to learn to read and write overnight, but slowly, step by step we&rsquo;ll get there!</p><p>Devanagari, or&nbsp;<big><big>&#2342;&#2375;&#2357;&#2344;&#2366;&#2327;&#2352;&#2368;</big></big>, is the name of the alphabet that Hindi is written in. Devanagari is also used to write other languages, like Sanskrit, Nepali, Marathi and so on. Each language has it&rsquo;s own slight modification to the alphabet - this is just like how the Latin alphabet (the one we&rsquo;re using here!) is used for other languages like Spanish and French, which have their own modifications - like the letter &eacute; in French and &ntilde; in Spanish.</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/bb2ad134d9354db52807aa6bbd20cd2e/tumblr_inline_mnhcrvGwU01qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center">These are the <a href="http://t.umblr.com/redirect?z=http%3A%2F%2Flearning-hindi.com%2Fvowels&amp;t=NmEwNWU5NzRkODE1ZTgzZDlkOGVlYjVjOWRmZDk1NmIxNmNjNzliNixQQUVpMjlZQg%3D%3D&amp;b=t%3Ahf3yIetu6VvjxJqY6DH92g&amp;p=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.learning-hindi.com%2Fpost%2F1021543673%2Fintro-3-devanagari-the-hindi-alphabet&amp;m=0">Hindi vowels</a> - do you recon they look a little scary? <br>Well don&rsquo;t be put off, we&rsquo;re here to teach you it all!</p><p>Now I&rsquo;m going to tell you a fact you might not believe, ready? Compared to English, Hindi is <em>much much</em> easier to read! See I told you you wouldn&rsquo;t believe me. So let me tell you why. This about the words &lsquo;cat&rsquo; and 'city&rsquo;, these both start with the letter 'c&rsquo;, but they start with different sounds! Cat starts with a 'k&rsquo; sound and city and &rsquo;s&rsquo; sound. Confusing hey! In Hindi every letters<em> always</em> has the same pronunciation*.</p><p>So let&rsquo;s learn a few things about Devanagari. Firstly the most distinctive look about it is the horizontal line that&rsquo;s above almost all the letters, it looks like a washing line with the letters hanging from it!</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/7e27f75bc7ba45975e4960f4ec2c9fea/tumblr_inline_mh8khp22zf1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><em>namaste aap kaise hain?</em> - Hello, how are you? <br>Notice how the letters hang from the red 'washing line&rsquo;</p><p>There are no capital letters in Devanagari - which makes our life a lot easier! We use something called a transliteration to help us read the Hindi words, what does this mean? Well for example here&rsquo;s a Hindi word: <big><big>&#2346;&#2381;&#2351;&#2366;&#2352; </big></big>it means 'love&rsquo; in Hindi. A transliteration tells us how to pronounce this word by writing it in English letters, so for this word we&rsquo;d write <em>pyaar - </em>that&rsquo;s approximately how the word is pronounced! The transliteration will always be in <em>italics </em>- but you should not learn to rely on it!</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/a27d149ebe34aab4a92e78ffd228d4b8/tumblr_inline_mnhctovDH41qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center">Everyone gets confused learning new things<br> - but stick with it and you&rsquo;ll get there!</p><p>Punctuation marks are exactly the same as English ones but sometimes you&rsquo;ll see a&nbsp;<big><big>&#2404;</big></big> which means exactly the same as a full stop (/period).</p><p>Hopefully this has given you enough background information for you to progress on to the&nbsp;<a href="../../vowels">Hindi Vowels</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href="../../consonants">Hindi Consonants</a>&nbsp;sections&nbsp;where you start to learn the letters of Devanagari in detail:</p><h2><a href="../../vowels">Hindi Vowels</a></h2><h2><a href="../../consonants">Hindi Consonants</a></h2><p>Are you having problems displaying Devanagari correctly on your computer? <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/1075556637/problems-viewing-the-site">Have a look here</a> to hopefully solve your issues.&nbsp;</p><p>*Ok I lied slightly, not 100% always. But the number of exceptions to the rules are microscopic especially when compared to English!</p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/aug2010">aug2010</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/introduction">introduction</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="1021543673" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_1021543673"><iframe id="like_iframe_1021543673" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=1021543673&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=PAEi29YB" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="0" class="like_toggle" allowTransparency="true" name="like_iframe_1021543673"></iframe></div><a href="https://www.tumblr.com/reblog/1021543673/PAEi29YB" class="reblog_button"style="display: block;width:16px;height:16px;"><svg width="100%" height="100%" viewBox="0 0 21 21" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" fill="#ccc"><path d="M5.01092527,5.99908429 L16.0088498,5.99908429 L16.136,9.508 L20.836,4.752 L16.136,0.083 L16.1360004,3.01110845 L2.09985349,3.01110845 C1.50585349,3.01110845 0.979248041,3.44726568 0.979248041,4.45007306 L0.979248041,10.9999998 L3.98376463,8.30993634 L3.98376463,6.89801007 C3.98376463,6.20867902 4.71892527,5.99908429 5.01092527,5.99908429 Z"></path><path d="M17.1420002,13.2800293 C17.1420002,13.5720293 17.022957,14.0490723 16.730957,14.0490723 L4.92919922,14.0490723 L4.92919922